@endnode

@node "gb" "Gameboy Emu Vs GameBoy Emu"

@{fg shine} Gameboy emulators put to the test@{fg text}

           Although the Amiga is the best computer in the world sometimes we like to
 emulate other formats for whatever reason. The Gameboy is a good platform to emulate
 as most of the games on the Gameboy are not avalible for the Amiga. We have got two
 of the best known Gameboy emulators for the Amiga and 'put them to the test'.

           First off is @{b}WzonkaladV0.68@{ub}. When you load Wzonkalad up you are
 presented with a nice looking screen with separate windows with different option
 to do different things. Wzonkalad is easy enough to use and isn't to complicated, you
 load in your cartridge and press play. Although Woznkalad looks nice with the Gameboy
 game in a WB window it is very slow on an A1200, 6Mb ram. To get Wzonkalad going at
 a fast pace you would probably have to have a fast processor although I havn't tryed
 that out. Wzonkalad looks nice and has a lot of features but the speed of the games
 are unplayable on my computer.

           Next we tryed @{b}AmiGameBoyV0.85@{ub}. AmiGameBoy is alot better, the layout is
 more clearer and the options are easyly spotted. The only major problem I had with the
 AmiGameBoy is that Mario2 didn't work were as on Wzonkalad it worked fine. AmiGameBoy
 is undoubtaly the best of the two Gameboy emulators as the speed is just fantastic,
 although you lose out on the games being in a WB window you gain on the size of the
 screen and most importantly the speed. AmiGameBoy does not emulate the games as fast
 as a real Gameboy but they are fast enough to play and thats what matters.

 @{b}Wzonkalad V0.68@{ub}                               @{b}AmiGameBoy V0.85@{ub}

 Presentation : 88%                            Presentation : 86%
 Ease of use  : 87%                            Ease of use  : 89%
 Speed        : 72%                            Speed        : 91%

 Overall      : 84%                            Overall      : 89%

 The overall winner is : @{b}AmiGameBoy@{ub}

     @{" Main Menu " link "Main" } @{" Features Menu " link "fea" }
@endnode

@node "wz" "Wzonkalad V0.80 tutorial"

@{fg shine} Wzonkalad Tutorial@{fg text}

 Part 1 : The basics (Issue 3 - This issue)
 Part 2 : Getting the hang of things (Issue 4)

 @{b}Part 1 :@{ub}

           Upon loading WzonkaLad you will be presented with a requester to ask
 you what screenmode you want WzonkaLad in. It is best to go for High-Res or whatever
 your WB screen is in. Once you have past that quit the 'About' window that appears
 and you will find yourself at the main menu. The top window named 'Wzonka-Lad' is
 the game screen where most games will be displayed in, the middle window is the
 options and the bottom window is the cartridge information. There isn't anything
 to change on the top window except where it is placed. Next we come to the options
 window named 'Menu' you will notice 9 buttons in the window. When you load up
 Wzonkalad you will notice that only four buttons are usable and the others are
 'fuzzed' out. The other options will appear once you have choosen a cartridge, below
 is a detailed description of what each button entails.

 (from left to right)

 /\\
 --      =  Reset the emulator, and restart the loaded cartridge

 >>>     =  Load a cartridge

 >       =  Play the current loaded cartridge

 ||      =  Stop the current cartridge

  _
 | |     =  Open/Close Cartridge Information window
   .
   #
  _
 | |     =  Open/Close About window
   |
   .

  P      =  Open Preferences window


 ||
 \\/      =  Save a GBS snapshot (Save game)
 ##
 ##

 /\\
 ||      =  Load a GBS snapshot (Load game)
 ##
 ##

 And last is the 'Cartridge Information' window. The options are listed below.

 Name  :  -  Tells you the name of the cartridge

 Rom   :  -  Tells you how much rom to game uses

 Ram   :  -  Tells you how much ram to game uses

 MFRER :  -  Company who produced the cartridge name.

 @{b}NEXT MONTH@{ub} - We'll look at the preferences and all the advanced options.

